# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-appsync
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Clients often use this in combination with autoscaling (a process that allows a client to use more computing in times of high application usage, and then scale down to reduce costs when there is less traffic).
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] These cloud computing web services provide various services related to networking, compute, storage, middleware, IoT and other processing capacity, as well as software tools via AWS server farms.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] This frees clients from managing, scaling, and patching hardware and operating systems.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] One of the foundational services is Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), which allows users to have at their disposal a virtual cluster of computers, with extremely high availability, which can be interacted with over the internet via REST APIs, a CLI or the AWS console.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] AWS services are delivered to customers via a network of AWS server farms located throughout the world.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Fees are based on a combination of usage (known as a "Pay-as-you-go" model), hardware, operating system, software, and networking features chosen by the subscriber requiring various degrees of availability, redundancy, security, and service options.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Subscribers can pay for a single virtual AWS computer, a dedicated physical computer, or clusters of either.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Amazon provides select portions of security for subscribers (e.g. physical security of the data centers) while other aspects of security are the responsibility of the subscriber (e.g. account management, vulnerability scanning, patching).
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] AWS operates from many global geographical regions, including nine in North America.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Amazon markets AWS to subscribers as a way of obtaining large-scale computing capacity more quickly and cheaply than building an actual physical server farm.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] All services are billed based on usage, but each service measures usage in varying ways.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] As of 2023 Q1, AWS has 31% market share for cloud infrastructure while the next two competitors Microsoft Azure and Google Cloud have 25%, and 11% respectively, according to Synergy Research Group.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] As of 2025 AWS comprises over 200 products and services including computing, storage, networking, database, analytics, application services, deployment, management, machine learning, mobile, developer tools, RobOps and tools for the Internet of Things.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] The most popular include Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3), Amazon Connect, and AWS Lambda (a serverless function that can perform arbitrary code written in any language that can be configured to be triggered by hundreds of events, including HTTP calls).
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Services expose functionality through APIs for clients to use in their applications.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] These APIs are accessed over HTTP, using the REST architectural style and SOAP protocol for older APIs and exclusively JSON for newer ones.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Clients can interact with these APIs in various ways, including from the AWS console (a website), by using SDKs written in various languages (such as Python, Java, and JavaScript), or by making direct REST calls.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] The genesis of AWS came in the early 2000s.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] After building *Merchant.com*, Amazon's e-commerce-as-a-service platform that offers third-party retailers a way to build their own web-stores, Amazon pursued service-oriented architecture as a means to scale its engineering operations, led by then CTO Allan Vermeulen.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] He also called for increasing the percentage of the time engineers spent building the software rather than doing other tasks.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Amazon created "a shared IT platform" so its engineering organizations, which were spending 70% of their time on "undifferentiated heavy-lifting" such as IT and infrastructure problems, could focus on customer-facing innovation instead.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In July 2002 Amazon.com Web Services, managed by Colin Bryar, launched its first web services, opening up the Amazon.com platform to all developers.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Over one hundred applications were built on top of it by 2004.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] This unexpected developer interest took Amazon by surprise and convinced them that developers were "hungry for more".
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] By the summer of 2003, Andy Jassy had taken over Bryar's portfolio at Rick Dalzell's behest, after Vermeulen, who was Bezos' first pick, declined the offer.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Jassy subsequently mapped out the vision for an "Internet OS" made up of foundational infrastructure primitives that alleviated key impediments to shipping software applications faster.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] By fall 2003, databases, storage, and compute were identified as the first set of infrastructure pieces that Amazon should launch.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] According to Brewster Kahle, co-founder of Alexa Internet, which was acquired by Amazon in 1999, his start-up's compute infrastructure helped Amazon solve its big data problems and later informed the innovations that underpinned AWS.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Jassy assembled a founding team of 57 employees from a mix of engineering and business backgrounds to kick-start these initiatives, with a majority of the hires coming from outside the company.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] They included Jeff Lawson, the Twilio CEO; Adam Selipsky, the Tableau CEO; and Mikhail Seregine, a co-founder at Outschool.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Near the end of their paper, they mentioned the possibility of selling access to virtual servers as a service, proposing the company could generate revenue from the new infrastructure investment.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Thereafter Pinkham, Willem van Biljon, and lead developer Christopher Brown developed the Amazon EC2 service, with a team in Cape Town, South Africa.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In October 2004, Amazon released Alexa Web Information Service (AWIS) as beta.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In November 2004, AWS launched its first infrastructure service, as beta: Simple Queue Service (SQS)., and officially launched in July 2006.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] On March 14, 2006, AWS launched Amazon S3 cloud storage, and that was the first AWS' IaaS that was generally available, followed by EC2 in August 2006.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Pi Corporation, a startup Paul Maritz co-founded, was the first beta-user of EC2 outside of Amazon, while Microsoft was among EC2's first enterprise customers.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Later that year SmugMug, one of the early AWS adopters, attributed savings of around US$400,000 in storage costs to S3.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] According to Vogels, S3 was built with 8 microservices when it launched in 2006 and had over 300 microservices by 2022.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In September 2007, AWS announced its annual *Start-up Challenge*, a contest with prizes worth $100,000 for entrepreneurs and software developers in the US using AWS services such as S3 and EC2 to build their businesses.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] The first edition saw participation from Justin.tv, which Amazon later acquired in 2014.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Ooyala, an online media company, was the eventual winner.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] AWS offers, as of June 16, 2022, two block-storage options: the EC2 Instance Store and the Elastic Block Store (EBS).
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Additional AWS services from this period include SimpleDB, Mechanical Turk, Elastic Beanstalk, Relational Database Service, DynamoDB, CloudWatch, Simple Workflow, CloudFront, and Availability Zones.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In November 2010, it was reported that all of Amazon.com's retail sites had migrated to AWS.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Prior to 2012, AWS was considered a part of Amazon.com and so its revenue was not delineated in Amazon financial statements.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In that year industry watchers for the first time estimated AWS revenue to be over $1.5 billion.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] On November 27, 2012, AWS hosted its first major annual conference, *re:Invent* with a focus on AWS's partners and ecosystem, with over 150 sessions.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] The three-day event was held in Las Vegas because of its relatively cheaper connectivity with locations across the United States and the rest of the world.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Andy Jassy and Werner Vogels presented keynotes, with Jeff Bezos joining Vogels for a fireside chat.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] AWS opened early registrations at US$1,099 per head for their customers from over 190 countries.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] On stage with Andy Jassy at the event which saw around 6000 attendees, Reed Hastings, CEO at Netflix, announced plans to migrate 100% of Netflix's infrastructure to AWS.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] To support industry-wide training and skills standardization, AWS began offering a certification program for computer engineers, on April 30, 2013, to highlight expertise in cloud computing.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Later that year, in October, AWS launched *Activate*, a program for start-ups worldwide to leverage AWS credits, third-party integrations, and free access to AWS experts to help build their business.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS launched its partner network, AWS Partner Network (APN), which is focused on helping AWS-based companies grow and scale the success of their business with close collaboration and best practices.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In October 2014, Amazon Aurora was launched.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In January 2015, Amazon Web Services acquired Annapurna Labs, an Israel-based microelectronics company for a reported US$350–370M.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In April 2015, Amazon.com reported AWS was profitable, with sales of $1.57 billion in the first quarter of the year and $265 million of operating income.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Founder Jeff Bezos described it as a fast-growing $5 billion business; analysts described it as "surprisingly more profitable than forecast".
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In October, Amazon.com said in its Q3 earnings report that AWS's operating income was $521 million, with operating margins at 25 percent.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] AWS's 2015 Q3 revenue was $2.1 billion, a 78% increase from 2014's Q3 revenue of $1.17 billion.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] 2015 Q4 revenue for the AWS segment increased 69.5% y/y to $2.4 billion with a 28.5% operating margin, giving AWS a $9.6 billion run rate.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In 2015, Gartner estimated that AWS customers are deploying 10x more infrastructure on AWS than the combined adoption of the next 14 providers.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In 2016 Q1, revenue was $2.57 billion with net income of $604 million, a 64% increase over 2015 Q1 that resulted in AWS being more profitable than Amazon's North American retail business for the first time.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Jassy was thereafter promoted to CEO of the division.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Around the same time, Amazon experienced a 42% rise in stock value as a result of increased earnings, of which AWS contributed 56% to corporate profits.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] AWS had $17.46 billion in annual revenue in 2017.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] By the end of 2020, the number had grown to $46 billion.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Reflecting the success of AWS, Jassy's annual compensation in 2017 hit nearly $36 million.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In January 2018, Amazon launched a unified autoscaling service on AWS.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] This new service unifies and builds on AWS existing, service-specific, scaling features like EC2 Auto Scaling groups, that was launched in August 2006.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In November 2018, AWS announced customized ARM cores for use in its servers.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Also in November 2018, AWS created ground stations to communicate with customers' satellites.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In 2019, AWS reported 37% yearly growth and accounted for 12% of Amazon's revenue (up from 11% in 2018).
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In April 2021, AWS reported 32% yearly growth and accounted for 32% of $41.8 billion cloud market in Q1 2021.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In January 2022, AWS joined the MACH Alliance, a non-profit enterprise technology advocacy group.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, it was reported that in 2019 Capital One had not secured their AWS resources properly, and was subject to a data breach by a former AWS employee.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] The employee was convicted of hacking into the company's cloud servers to steal customer data and use computer power to mine cryptocurrency.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] The ex-employee was able to download the personal information of more than 100 million Capital One customers.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, AWS announced they had launched the AWS Snowcone, a small computing device, to the International Space Station on the Axiom Mission 1.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In September 2023, AWS announced it would become AI startup Anthropic's primary cloud provider.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Amazon has committed to investing up to $4 billion in Anthropic and will have a minority ownership position in the company.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, AWS announced a new service called Deadline Cloud, which lets customers set up, deploy and scale up graphics and visual effects rendering pipelines on AWS cloud infrastructure.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In July 2024, AWS won a $1.3 billion (A$2 billion) contract with Australia's government to build a top-secret cloud service.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] The service included a partnership with the Australian Signals Directorate (ASD).
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] The ASD director general Rachel Noble said the service would "provide a state-of-the-art collaborative space for our intelligence and defense community to store and access top-secret data”.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In December 2024, AWS announced Amazon Nova, its own family of foundation models.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] These models, offered through Amazon Bedrock, are designed for various tasks including content generation, video understanding, and building agentic applications.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] They are available in six different sizes.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In March and April of 2026, during the 2026 Iran War, Iranian drone and missile strikes damaged AWS data centers in the United Arab Emirates (me-central-1) and Bahrain (me-south-1) regions, in the first deliberate military targeting of a commercial data center.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Iran claimed the data centers hosted US military workloads.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] AWS advised customers to migrate to other regions.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In October 2013, AWS was awarded a $600M contract with the CIA.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] By 2019, it was reported that more than 80% of Germany's listed DAX companies used AWS.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Navy said it moved 72,000 users from six commands to an AWS cloud system as a first step toward pushing all of its data and analytics onto the cloud.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, Amazon announced that it would suspend Parler from Amazon Web Services, stating Parler hosted “violent content” that violates its terms of service.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Later in 2021, DISH Network announced it would develop and launch its 5G network on AWS.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] It was also reported that spy agencies and government departments in the UK, such as GCHQ, MI5, MI6, and the Ministry of Defence, contracted AWS to host their classified materials.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In 2022, Amazon shared a $9 billion contract from the United States Department of Defense for cloud computing with Google, Microsoft, and Oracle.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] AWS won a $581 million contract from the U.S.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Air Force in January 2026 to provide cloud services and specific Amazon data centers as part of the Cloud One Program, the Air Force's enterprise cloud environment.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Multiple financial services firms have shifted to AWS in some form.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Notable customers include NASA and the Obama presidential campaign of 2012.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] As of October 2025, AWS has distinct operations in 38 geographical "regions": nine in North America, two in South America, nine in Europe, four in the Middle East, one in Africa, thirteen in the Asia–Pacific, and three in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Most AWS regions are enabled by default for AWS accounts.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Regions introduced after 20 March 2019 are considered to be *opt-in* regions, requiring a user to explicitly enable them in order for the region to be usable in the account.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] For opt-in regions, Identity and Access Management (IAM) resources such as users and roles are only propagated to the regions that are enabled.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Each region is wholly contained within a single country and all of its data and services stay within the designated region.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Each region has multiple "Availability Zones", which consist of one or more discrete data centers, each with redundant power, networking, and connectivity, housed in separate facilities.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Availability Zones do not automatically provide additional scalability or redundancy within a region, since they are intentionally isolated from each other to prevent outages from spreading between zones.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Several services can operate across Availability Zones (e.g., S3, DynamoDB) while others can be configured to replicate across zones to spread demand and avoid downtime from failures.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] As of December 2014, Amazon Web Services operated an estimated 1.4 million servers across 11 regions and 28 availability zones.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] As of March 2024, AWS had announced the planned launch of six additional regions in Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Thailand, Saudi Arabia, and the European Union.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In mid March 2023, Amazon Web Services signed a cooperation agreement with the New Zealand Government to build large data centers in New Zealand.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] AWS also has "pop-up lofts" in different locations around the world.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] These market AWS to entrepreneurs and startups in different tech industries in a physical location.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Visitors can work or relax inside the loft, or learn more about what they can do with AWS.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In June 2014, AWS opened their first temporary pop-up loft in San Francisco.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In May 2015 they expanded to New York City, and in September 2015 expanded to Berlin.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] AWS opened its fourth location, in Tel Aviv from March 1, 2016, to March 22, 2016.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] A pop-up loft was open in London from September 10 to October 29, 2015.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] The pop-up lofts in New York and San Francisco are indefinitely closed due to the COVID-19 pandemic while Tokyo has remained open in a limited capacity.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In 2017, AWS launched AWS re/Start in the United Kingdom to help young adults and military veterans retrain in technology-related skills.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In partnership with the Prince's Trust and the Ministry of Defence (MoD), AWS will help to provide re-training opportunities for young people from disadvantaged backgrounds and former military personnel.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] AWS is working alongside a number of partner companies including Cloudreach, Sage Group, EDF Energy, and Tesco Bank.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In April 2022, AWS announced that the organization had committed more than $30 million over three years to early-stage start-ups led by Black, Latino, LGBTQIA+, and women founders as part of its AWS impact Accelerator.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] The Initiative offers qualifying start-ups up to $225,000 in cash, credits, extensive training, mentoring, technical guidance and includes up to $100,000 in AWS service credits.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS claimed its aim was to achieve 100% renewable energy usage in the future.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In 2016, Greenpeace assessed major tech companies—including cloud services providers like AWS, Microsoft, Oracle, Google, IBM, Salesforce and Rackspace—based on their level of "clean energy" usage.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace evaluated companies on their mix of renewable-energy sources; transparency; renewable-energy commitment and policies; energy efficiency and greenhouse-gas mitigation; renewable-energy procurement; and advocacy.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] The group gave AWS an overall "C" grade.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace credited AWS for its advances toward greener computing in recent years and its plans to launch multiple wind and solar farms across the United States.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] The organization stated that Amazon is opaque about its carbon footprint.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, AWS joined an industry pledge to achieve climate neutrality of data centers by 2030, the Climate Neutral Data Centre Pact.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] As of 2023, Amazon as a whole is the largest corporate purchaser of renewable energy in the world, a position it has held since 2020, and has a global portfolio of over 20 GW of renewable energy capacity.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In 2022, 90% of all Amazon operations, including data centers, were powered by renewables.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In 2024, AWS paid $650 million for a data center at the 2.5 GW Susquehanna nuclear power plant, connected at 300 MW.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] The power increase depends on Amazon's expansion of the data center.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] US Department of Homeland Security has employed the software ATLAS, which runs on Amazon Cloud.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] It scanned more than 16.5 million records of naturalized Americans and flagged approximately 124,000 of them for manual analysis and review by USCIS officers regarding denaturalization.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Some of the scanned data came from the Terrorist Screening Database and the National Crime Information Center.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] The algorithm and the criteria for the algorithm were secret.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Amazon faced protests from its own employees and activists for the anti-migrant collaboration with authorities.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] The contract for Project Nimbus drew rebuke and condemnation from the companies' shareholders as well as their employees, over concerns that the project would lead to abuses of Palestinians' human rights in the context of the ongoing occupation and the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Specifically, they voice concern over how the technology will enable further surveillance of Palestinians and unlawful data collection on them as well as facilitate the expansion of Israel's illegal settlements on Palestinian land.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] A government procurement document featuring 'obligatory customers' of Nimbus, including "two of Israel’s leading state-owned weapons manufacturers" Israel Aerospace Industries and Rafael Advanced Defense Systems, was published in 2021 with periodic updates since (up to Oct 2023).
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] AWS has been noted to work with Chinese companies under varying degrees of U.S. government sanctions, such as Hikvision and Dahua Technology, which have been accused to enabling mass surveillance and human rights abuses in China and elsewhere.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In July 2025, a security researcher disclosed a supply-chain vulnerability in the Amazon Q Developer Extension (version 1.84) for Visual Studio Code.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] The issue involved a malicious pull request to the project's GitHub repository, which introduced a prompt instructing the AI assistant to delete local files and AWS resources.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] AWS acknowledged the issue in Security Bulletin AWS‑2025‑015 and released version 1.85 to remove the injected prompt.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] The company stated that no customer systems or data were affected.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] However, critics including Corey Quinn, writing in Last Week in AWS, questioned the transparency of the response, noting the absence of a changelog entry, a CVE assignment, or a public statement beyond the bulletin.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In response to the Log4Shell vulnerability, AWS released hot patch solutions to mitigate risks in Java applications across various environments, including standalone servers, Kubernetes clusters, and Elastic Container Service (ECS).
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] These patches were designed for both AWS and non-AWS environments.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] However, researchers from Unit 42 at Palo Alto Networks identified critical security flaws in these patches that could be exploited for container escape and privilege escalation, potentially granting attackers unauthorized root-level access to the host system.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] AWS addressed these vulnerabilities by releasing updated patches on April 19, 2022.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Users who deployed the initial patches were advised to upgrade to the latest versions to mitigate security risks.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, security researchers from Miggo security identified a configuration vulnerability in AWS Application Load Balancer (ALB) that could allow attackers to bypass access controls and compromise web applications.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] The issue stemmed from how some users configured ALB's authentication handoff to third-party services, potentially enabling unauthorized access to application data.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] On July 11, 2024, AWS confirmed the issue affecting its customers, and on July 19, 2024, AWS updated its documentation accordingly to recommend more secure implementation practices.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] In 2026, Amazon Web Services (AWS) data center infrastructure in the United Arab Emirates and Bahrain experienced service disruptions following reported drone strikes in the region.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] AWS applies charges for data transferred both between Availability Zones within the same region (inter-AZ) and across different geographic regions (inter-region).
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] The pricing structure is influenced by several factors, including the source and destination of the data, the specific AWS services in use, and the underlying networking architecture.
[src:aws-appsync/amazon-web-services] Various services implement different data transfer models, and the choice of communication method—such as VPC Peering, Transit Gateway, or AWS PrivateLink—can also affect the overall cost.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] Facebook started GraphQL development in 2012 and released a draft specification and reference implementation as open source in 2015.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] In 2018, GraphQL was moved to the newly established GraphQL Foundation, hosted by the non-profit Linux Foundation.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] On February 9, 2018, the GraphQL Schema Definition Language became part of the specification.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] Many popular public APIs adopted GraphQL as the default way to access them.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] These include public APIs of Facebook, GitHub, Yelp, Shopify, Google Directions API and many others.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] There is an annual GraphQL Conference featuring new developments of the protocol and organizations successfully using GraphQL.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] The event is hosted by the GraphQL Foundation with previous organizers incl.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] GraphQL supports reading, writing (mutating), and subscribing to changes to data (realtime updates – commonly implemented using WebSockets).
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] A GraphQL service is created by defining types with fields, then providing functions to resolve the data for each field.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] The types and fields make up what is known as the *schema definition*.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] The functions that retrieve and map the data are called *resolvers*.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] After being validated against the schema, a GraphQL query is executed by the server.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] The server returns a result that mirrors the shape of the original query, typically as JSON.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] With GraphQL, a business domain is modeled as a graph by defining a schema; within this schema, different types of nodes and their relations are defined.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] The GraphQL type system describes what data can be queried from the API.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] The collection of those capabilities is referred to as the service's *schema* and clients can use that schema to send queries to the API that return predictable results.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] The root type of a GraphQL schema, `Query` by default, contains all of the fields that can be queried.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] Other types define the objects and fields that the GraphQL server can return.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] There are several base types, called scalars, to represent things like strings, numbers, and IDs.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] Fields are defined as nullable by default, and a trailing exclamation mark can be used to make a field non-nullable (required).
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] A field can be defined as a list by wrapping the field's type in square brackets (for example, `authors: [String]`).
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] A GraphQL query defines the exact shape of the data needed by the client.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] Once validated and executed by the GraphQL server, the data is returned in the same shape.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] A GraphQL mutation allows for data to be created, updated, or deleted.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] Mutations generally contain *variables*, which allow data to be passed into the server from the client.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] The mutation also defines the shape of the data that will be returned to the client after the operation is complete.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] The variables are passed as an object with fields that match the variable names in the mutation.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] Once the operation is complete, the GraphQL server will return data matching the shape defined by the mutation.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] GraphQL also supports live updates sent from the server to client in an operation called a subscription.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] Again, the client defines the shape of the data that it needs whenever an update is made.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] When a mutation is made through the GraphQL server that updates the associated field, data is sent to all subscribed clients in the format setup through the subscription.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] While there's nothing that prevents a GraphQL service from being versioned just like any other API, GraphQL takes a strong opinion on avoiding versioning by providing the tools for the continuous evolution of a GraphQL schema.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] The `@deprecated` *built-in directive* is used within the type system definition language to indicate deprecated portions of a GraphQL service's schema, such as deprecated fields on a type or deprecated enum values.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] GraphQL only returns the data that's explicitly requested, so new capabilities can be added via new types or new fields on existing types without creating a breaking change.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] This has led to a common practice of always avoiding breaking changes and serving a versionless API.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] GraphQL does not provide a full-fledged graph query language such as SPARQL, or even in dialects of SQL that support transitive closure.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] For example, a GraphQL interface that reports the parents of an individual cannot return, in a single query, the set of all their ancestors.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] GraphQL APIs can be tested manually or with automated tools issuing GraphQL requests and verifying the correctness of the results.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] Automatic test generation is also possible.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] New requests may be produced through search-based techniques due to a typed schema and introspection capabilities.
[src:aws-appsync/graphql] Some of the software tools used for testing GraphQL implementations include Postman, Beeceptor, GraphiQL, Apollo Studio, GraphQL Hive, GraphQL Editor, and Step CI.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] In push technology, clients can express their preferences for certain types of information or data, typically through a process known as the publish–subscribe model.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] In this model, a client "subscribes" to specific information channels hosted by a server.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] When new content becomes available on these channels, the server automatically sends, or "pushes," this information to the subscribed client.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] Under certain conditions, such as restrictive security policies that block incoming HTTP requests, push technology is sometimes simulated using a technique called polling.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] In these cases, the client periodically checks with the server to see if new information is available, rather than receiving automatic updates.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] Synchronous conferencing and instant messaging are examples of push services.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] Chat messages and sometimes files are pushed to the user as soon as they are received by the messaging service.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] Both decentralized peer-to-peer programs (such as WASTE) and centralized programs (such as IRC or XMPP) allow pushing files, which means the sender initiates the data transfer rather than the recipient.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] Email may also be a push system: SMTP is a push protocol (see Push e-mail).
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] However, the last step—from mail server to desktop computer—typically uses a pull protocol like POP3 or IMAP.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] Modern e-mail clients make this step seem instantaneous by repeatedly polling the mail server, frequently checking it for new mail.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] The IMAP protocol includes the IDLE command, which allows the server to tell the client when new messages arrive.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] The original BlackBerry was the first popular example of push-email in a wireless context.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] Another example is the PointCast Network, which was widely covered in the 1990s.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] It delivered news and stock market data as a screensaver.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] Both Netscape and Microsoft integrated push technology through the Channel Definition Format (CDF) into their software at the height of the browser wars, but it was never very popular.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] Other uses of push-enabled web applications include software updates distribution ("push updates"), market data distribution (stock tickers), online chat/messaging systems (webchat), auctions, online betting and gaming, sport results, monitoring consoles, and sensor network monitoring.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] The Web push proposal of the Internet Engineering Task Force is a simple protocol using HTTP version 2 to deliver real-time events, such as incoming calls or messages, which can be delivered (or "pushed") in a timely fashion.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] The protocol consolidates all real-time events into a single session which ensures more efficient use of network and radio resources.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] A single service consolidates all events, distributing those events to applications as they arrive.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] This requires just one session, avoiding duplicated overhead costs.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] Web Notifications are part of the W3C standard and define an API for end-user notifications.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] A notification allows alerting the user of an event, such as the delivery of an email, outside the context of a web page.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] As part of this standard, Push API is fully implemented in Chrome, Firefox, and Edge, and partially implemented in Safari as of February 2023.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] HTTP server push (also known as HTTP streaming) is a mechanism for sending unsolicited (asynchronous) data from a web server to a web browser.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] HTTP server push can be achieved through any of several mechanisms.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] As a part of HTML5 the Web Socket API allows a web server and client to communicate over a full-duplex TCP connection.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] Generally, the web server does not terminate a connection after response data has been served to a client.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] The web server leaves the connection open so that if an event occurs (for example, a change in internal data which needs to be reported to one or multiple clients), it can be sent out immediately; otherwise, the event would have to be queued until the client's next request is received.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] Most web servers offer this functionality via CGI (e.g., Non-Parsed Headers scripts on Apache HTTP Server).
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] The underlying mechanism for this approach is chunked transfer encoding.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] Another mechanism is related to a special MIME type called `multipart/x-mixed-replace`, which was introduced by Netscape in 1995.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] Web browsers interpret this as a document that changes whenever the server pushes a new version to the client.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] It is still supported by Firefox, Opera, and Safari today, but it is ignored by Internet Explorer and is only partially supported by Chrome.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] It can be applied to HTML documents, and also for streaming images in webcam applications.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] The WHATWG Web Applications 1.0 proposal includes a mechanism to push content to the client.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] On September 1, 2006, the Opera web browser implemented this new experimental system in a feature called "Server-Sent Events".
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] In this technique, the server takes advantage of persistent HTTP connections, leaving the response perpetually "open" (i.e., the server never terminates the response), effectively fooling the browser to remain in "loading" mode after the initial page load could be considered complete.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] The server then periodically sends snippets of JavaScript to update the content of the page, thereby achieving push capability.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] By using this technique, the client doesn't need Java applets or other plug-ins in order to keep an open connection to the server; the client is automatically notified about new events, pushed by the server.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] One serious drawback to this method, however, is the lack of control the server has over the browser timing out; a page refresh is always necessary if a timeout occurs on the browser end.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] Long polling is itself not a true push; long polling is a variation of the traditional polling technique, but it allows emulating a push mechanism under circumstances where a real push is not possible, such as sites with security policies that require rejection of incoming HTTP requests.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] With long polling, the client requests to get more information from the server exactly as in normal polling, but with the expectation that the server may not respond immediately.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] If the server has no new information for the client when the poll is received, then instead of sending an empty response, the server holds the request open and waits for response information to become available.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] Once it does have new information, the server immediately sends an HTTP response to the client, completing the open HTTP request.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] Upon receipt of the server response, the client often immediately issues another server request.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] In this way the usual response latency (the time between when the information first becomes available and the next client request) otherwise associated with polling clients is eliminated.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] This technique, used by chat applications, makes use of the XML Socket object in a single-pixel Adobe Flash movie.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] Under the control of JavaScript, the client establishes a TCP connection to a unidirectional relay on the server.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] The relay server does not read anything from this socket; instead, it immediately sends the client a unique identifier.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] Next, the client makes an HTTP request to the web server, including this identifier with it.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] The web application can then push messages addressed to the client to a local interface of the relay server, which relays them over the Flash socket.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] The advantage of this approach is that it appreciates the natural read-write asymmetry that is typical of many web applications, including chat, and as a consequence it offers high efficiency.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] Since it does not accept data on outgoing sockets, the relay server does not need to poll outgoing TCP connections *at all*, making it possible to hold open tens of thousands of concurrent connections.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] In this model, the limit to scale is the TCP stack of the underlying server operating system.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] In services such as cloud computing, to increase reliability and availability of data, it is usually pushed (replicated) to several machines.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] For example, the Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS) makes 2 extra copies of any object stored.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] RGDD focuses on efficiently casting an object from one location to many while saving bandwidth by sending minimal number of copies (only one in the best case) of the object over any link across the network.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] For example, Datacast is a scheme for delivery to many nodes inside data centers that relies on regular and structured topologies and DCCast is a similar approach for delivery across data centers.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] A push notification is a message that is "pushed" from a back-end server or application to a user interface, e.g. mobile applications or desktop applications.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] Apple introduced push notifications for iPhone in 2009, and in 2010 Google released "Google Cloud to Device Messaging" (superseded by Google Cloud Messaging and then by Firebase Cloud Messaging).
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] Push notifications are mainly divided into two approaches, local notifications and remote notifications.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] For local notifications, the application schedules the notification with the local device's OS.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] The application sets a timer in the application itself, provided it is able to continuously run in the background.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] When the event's scheduled time is reached, or the event's programmed condition is met, the message is displayed in the application's user interface.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] Remote notifications are handled by a remote server.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] Under this scenario, the client application needs to be registered on the server with a unique key (e.g., a UUID or Apple *Device Token*).
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] The server then transmits the message against the unique key to deliver it to the client via an agreed client/server protocol such as HTTP or XMPP.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] When the push notification arrives at the client, it can cause the display of short notifications or messages, set badges on application icons, blink or continuously light up the notification LED, or play alert sounds to attract user's attention.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] Push notifications are usually used by applications to bring information to users' attention.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] Real-time push notifications may raise privacy issues since they can be used to bind virtual identities of social network pseudonyms to the real identities of the smartphone owners.
[src:aws-appsync/push-technology] The use of unnecessary push notifications for promotional purposes has been criticized as an example of attention theft.
[src:aws-appsync/real-time-web] The **real-time web** is a network web using technologies and practices that enable users to receive information as soon as it is published by its authors, rather than requiring that they or their software check a source periodically for updates.
[src:aws-appsync/real-time-web] Examples of real-time web are Facebook's newsfeed, and Twitter, implemented in social networking, search, and news sites.
[src:aws-appsync/real-time-web] Benefits are said to include increased user engagement ("flow") and decreased server loads.
[src:aws-appsync/real-time-web] In December 2009 real-time search facilities were added to Google Search.
[src:aws-appsync/real-time-web] The true-realtime web model was born in 2000 at mc2labs.net by an Italian independent researcher.
[src:aws-appsync/real-time-web] A problem created by the rapid pace and huge volume of information created by real-time web technologies and practices is finding relevant information.
[src:aws-appsync/real-time-web] One approach, known as **real-time search**, is the concept of searching for and finding information online as it is produced.
[src:aws-appsync/real-time-web] Advancements in web search technology coupled with growing use of social media enable online activities to be queried as they occur.
[src:aws-appsync/real-time-web] A traditional web search crawls and indexes web pages periodically, returning results based on relevance to the search query.
[src:aws-appsync/real-time-web] Google Real-Time Search was available in Google Search until July 2011.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] In a web service, a web technology such as HTTP is used for transferring machine-readable file formats such as XML and JSON.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] In practice, a web service commonly provides an object-oriented web-based interface to a database server, utilized for example by another web server, or by a mobile app, that provides a user interface to the end-user.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] Many organizations that provide data in formatted HTML pages will also provide that data on their server as XML or JSON, often through a Web service to allow syndication.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] Another application offered to the end-user may be a mashup, where a Web server consumes several Web services at different machines and compiles the content into one user interface.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] Asynchronous JavaScript and XML (AJAX) is a dominant technology for Web services.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] Developing from the combination of HTTP servers, JavaScript clients and Plain Old XML (as distinct from SOAP and W3C Web Services), now it is frequently used with JSON as well as, or instead of, XML.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] Representational State Transfer (REST) is an architecture for well-behaved Web services that can function at Internet scale.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] A Web API is a development in Web services where emphasis has been moving to simpler representational state transfer (REST) based communications.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] Restful APIs do not require XML-based Web service protocols (SOAP and WSDL) to support their interfaces.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] W3C Web Services may use SOAP over HTTP protocol, allowing less costly (more efficient) interactions over the Internet than via proprietary solutions like EDI/B2B.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] Besides SOAP over HTTP, Web services can also be implemented on other reliable transport mechanisms like FTP.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] The term "Web service" describes a standardized way of integrating Web-based applications using the XML, SOAP, WSDL and UDDI open standards over an Internet Protocol backbone.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] XML is the data format used to contain the data and provide metadata around it, SOAP is used to transfer the data, WSDL is used for describing the services available and UDDI lists what services are available.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] A Web service is a method of communication between two electronic devices over a network.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] It is a software function provided at a network address over the Web with the service *always-on* as in the concept of utility computing.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] Many organizations use multiple software systems for management.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] Different software systems often need to exchange data with each other, and a Web service is a method of communication that allows two software systems to exchange this data over the Internet.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] The software system that requests data is called a *service requester*, whereas the software system that would process the request and provide the data is called a *service provider*.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] Different software may use different programming languages, and hence there is a need for a method of data exchange that doesn't depend upon a particular programming language.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] Most types of software can, however, interpret XML tags.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] Thus, Web services can use XML files for data exchange.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] All of these rules for communication are defined in a file called WSDL (Web Services Description Language), which has a `.wsdl` extension.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] A directory called UDDI (Universal Description, Discovery, and Integration) defines which software system should be contacted for which type of data.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] So when one software system needs one particular report/data, it would go to the UDDI and find out which other systems it can contact for receiving that data.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] Once the software system finds out which other systems it should contact, it would then contact that system using a special protocol called SOAP (Simple Object Access Protocol).
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] The service provider system would first validate the data request by referring to the WSDL file, and then process the request and send the data under the SOAP protocol.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] Automated tools can aid in the creation of a Web service.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] For services using WSDL, it is possible to either automatically generate WSDL for existing classes (a bottom-up model) or to generate a class skeleton given existing WSDL (a top-down model).
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] Critics of non-RESTful Web services often complain that they are too complex and based upon large software vendors or integrators, rather than typical open source implementations.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] There are also concerns about performance due to Web services' use of XML as a message format and SOAP/HTTP in enveloping and transporting.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] Functional and non-functional testing of Web services is done with the help of WSDL parsing.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] Regression testing is performed by identifying the changes made to upgrade software.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] Web service regression testing needs can be categorized in three different ways, namely, changes in WSDL, changes in the code, and selective re-testing of operations.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] We can capture the above three needs in three intermediate forms of Subset WSDL, namely, Difference WSDL (DWSDL), Unit WSDL (UWSDL), and Reduced WSDL (RWSDL), respectively.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] These three Subset WSDLs are then combined to form Combined WSDL (CWSDL) that is further used for regression testing of the Web service.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] This will help in Automated Web Service Change Management (AWSCM), by performing the selection of the relevant test cases to construct a reduced test suite from the old test suite.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] Web services testing can also be automated using several test automation tools like SoapUI, Oracle Application Testing Suite (OATS), Unified Functional Testing, Selenium, etc.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] Work-related to the capture and visualization of changes made to a Web service.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] Visualization and computation of changes can be done in the form of intermediate artifacts (Subset WSDL).
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] The insight on the computation of change impact is helpful in testing, top-down development and reduce regression testing.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] AWSCM is a tool that can identify subset operations in a WSDL file to construct a subset WSDL.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] While UDDI was intended to serve as a service directory and become the means to discovering web services, many vendors discontinued their UDDI solutions or repositories between 2005 and 2008, including Microsoft, SAP, IBM, among others.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] A key study published in WWW2008 Conference (Beijing, China) presented the state of SOAP-based web services and concluded that only 63% of the available SOAP-based web services at the time of the study were actually active or can be invoked.
[src:aws-appsync/web-service] The study also found that search engines were becoming an ideal source for searching for web services compared to that of service registries like the UDDI due its design complexity.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] WebSocket is distinct from HTTP used to serve most webpages.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] Although they are different, RFC 6455 states that WebSocket "is designed to work over HTTP ports 443 and 80 as well as to support HTTP proxies and intermediaries", making the WebSocket protocol compatible with HTTP.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] To achieve compatibility, the WebSocket handshake uses the HTTP Upgrade header to change from the HTTP protocol to the WebSocket protocol.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] The WebSocket protocol enables full-duplex interaction between a web browser (or other client application) and a web server with lower overhead than half-duplex alternatives such as HTTP polling, facilitating real-time data transfer from and to the server.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] This is achieved by providing a standardized way for the server to send content to the client without being first requested by the client, and allowing messages to be exchanged while keeping the connection open.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] In this way, a two-way ongoing conversation can take place between the client and the server.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] The communications are usually done over TCP port number 443 (or 80 in the case of unsecured connections), which is beneficial for environments that block non-web Internet connections using a firewall.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] Additionally, WebSocket enables streams of messages on top of TCP.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] TCP alone deals with streams of bytes with no inherent concept of a message.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] Similar two-way browser–server communications have been achieved in non-standardized ways using stopgap technologies such as Comet or Adobe Flash Player.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] Most browsers support the protocol, including Google Chrome, Firefox, Microsoft Edge, Internet Explorer, Safari and Opera.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] The WebSocket protocol specification defines `ws` (WebSocket) and `wss` (WebSocket Secure) as two new uniform resource identifier (URI) schemes that are used for unencrypted and encrypted connections respectively.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] Apart from the scheme name and fragment (i.e.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] `#` is not supported), the rest of the URI components are defined to use URI generic syntax.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] WebSocket was first referenced as TCPConnection in the HTML5 specification, as a placeholder for a TCP-based socket API.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] In June 2008, a series of discussions were led by Michael Carter that resulted in the first version of the protocol known as WebSocket.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] Before WebSocket, port 80 full-duplex communication was attainable using Comet channels; however, Comet implementation is nontrivial, and due to the TCP handshake and HTTP header overhead, it is inefficient for small messages.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] The WebSocket protocol aims to solve these problems without compromising the security assumptions of the web.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] The name "WebSocket" was coined by Ian Hickson and Michael Carter shortly thereafter through collaboration on the #whatwg IRC chat room, and subsequently authored for inclusion in the HTML5 specification by Ian Hickson.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] In December 2009, Google Chrome 4 was the first browser to ship full support for the standard, with WebSocket enabled by default.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] Development of the WebSocket protocol was subsequently moved from the W3C and WHATWG group to the IETF in February 2010, and authored for two revisions under Ian Hickson.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] After the protocol was shipped and enabled by default in multiple browsers, the RFC 6455 was finalized under Ian Fette in December 2011.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] RFC 7692 introduced compression extension to WebSocket using the DEFLATE algorithm on a per-message basis.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] A web application (e.g. web browser) may use the `WebSocket` interface to maintain bidirectional communications with a WebSocket server.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] **Frame-based message** exchange: data, ping and pong messages.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] **Closing handshake**: close message (request then echoed in response).
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] The client sends an **HTTP request** (**method** **GET**, **version ≥ 1.1**) and the server returns an **HTTP response** with **status code 101** (*Switching Protocols*) on success.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] HTTP and WebSocket clients can connect to a server using the same port because the opening handshake uses HTTP.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] Sending additional HTTP headers (that are not in the table below) is allowed.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] After the *Switching Protocols* HTTP response, the opening handshake is complete, the HTTP protocol stops being used, and communication switches to a binary frame-based protocol.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] The following Python code generates a random `Sec-WebSocket-Key`.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] The following Python code calculates `Sec-WebSocket-Accept` using `Sec-WebSocket-Key` from the example request above.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] `Sec-WebSocket-Key` and `Sec-WebSocket-Accept` are intended to prevent a caching proxy from re-sending a previous WebSocket conversation, and does not provide any authentication, privacy, or integrity.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] Though some servers accept a short `Sec-WebSocket-Key`, many modern servers will reject the request with error "invalid Sec-WebSocket-Key header".
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] After the opening handshake, the client and server can, at any time, send **data messages** (text or binary) and **control messages** (*Close*, *Ping*, *Pong*) to each other.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] A message is composed of **one frame if unfragmented** or **at least two frames if fragmented**.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] A **client must mask** all frames sent to the server.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] A **server must not mask** any frames sent to the client.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] Frame masking applies **XOR between the payload and the masking key**.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] The following pseudocode describes the algorithm used to both mask and unmask a frame.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] The `permessage-deflate` extension allows data messages to be compressed using the DEFLATE algorithm.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] For example, during the opening handshake, the client and server may use the following header to enable the extension.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] The `RSV1` field of the first frame of a data message must be set to indicate the payload data is compressed.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] Note: `recv()` returns up to the amount of bytes requested.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] For readability, the code ignores that, thus it may fail in non-ideal network conditions.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] A secure version of the WebSocket protocol is implemented in Firefox 6, Safari 6, Google Chrome 14, Opera 12.10 and Internet Explorer 10.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] A detailed protocol test suite report lists the conformance of those browsers to specific protocol aspects.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] An older, less secure version of the protocol was implemented in Opera 11 and Safari 5, as well as the mobile version of Safari in iOS 4.2.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] The BlackBerry Browser in OS7 implements WebSockets.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] Because of vulnerabilities, it was disabled in Firefox 4 and 5, and Opera 11.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] Using browser developer tools, developers can inspect the WebSocket handshake as well as the WebSocket frames.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] ASP.NET Core have support for WebSockets using the `app.UseWebSockets();` middleware.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] Unlike regular cross-domain HTTP requests, WebSocket requests are not restricted by the same-origin policy.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] It is better to use tokens or similar protection mechanisms to authenticate the WebSocket connection when sensitive (private) data is being transferred over the WebSocket.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] A live example of vulnerability was seen in 2020 in the form of Cable Haunt.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] WebSocket protocol client implementations try to detect whether the user agent is configured to use a proxy when connecting to destination host and port, and if it is, uses HTTP CONNECT method to set up a persistent tunnel.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] The WebSocket protocol is unaware of proxy servers and firewalls.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] Some proxy servers are transparent and work fine with WebSocket; others will prevent WebSocket from working correctly, causing the connection to fail.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] In some cases, additional proxy-server configuration may be required, and certain proxy servers may need to be upgraded to support WebSocket.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] If unencrypted WebSocket traffic flows through an explicit or a transparent proxy server without WebSockets support, the connection will likely fail.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] If an encrypted WebSocket connection is used, then the use of Transport Layer Security (TLS) in the WebSocket Secure connection ensures that an `HTTP CONNECT` command is issued when the browser is configured to use an explicit proxy server.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] This sets up a tunnel, which provides low-level end-to-end TCP communication through the HTTP proxy, between the WebSocket Secure client and the WebSocket server.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] In the case of transparent proxy servers, the browser is unaware of the proxy server, so no `HTTP CONNECT` is sent.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] However, since the wire traffic is encrypted, intermediate transparent proxy servers may simply allow the encrypted traffic through, so there is a much better chance that the WebSocket connection will succeed if WebSocket Secure is used.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] Using encryption is not free of resource cost, but often provides the highest success rate, since it would be travelling through a secure tunnel.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] A mid-2010 draft (version hixie-76) broke compatibility with reverse proxies and gateways by including eight bytes of key data after the headers, but not advertising that data in a `Content-Length: 8` header.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] This data was not forwarded by all intermediates, which could lead to protocol failure.
[src:aws-appsync/websocket] More recent drafts (e.g., hybi-09) put the key data in a `Sec-WebSocket-Key` header, solving this problem.
